  "texts": [
    "This is worth noting because, in many papers, singletons are assumed to be salient.",
    "In Fig. 3e, the central stimulus is the only red stimulus, but as all other stimuli have their unique color as well, most researchers will not refer to it as a singleton.",
    "Finally, in Fig. 3f, the single red stimulus on the left is a singleton locally (in the left part of the display) but not globally (across the whole display).",
    "The terms first-order versus second-order features have been used to refer to absolute versus relative features of singletons (Gaspelin & Luck, 2018a), but these terms are not to be confused with first-versus second-order image statistics (Julesz, 1975; Lu & Sperling, 2001).",
    "A stimulus either is or is not a singleton."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The terms first-order versus second-order features have been used to refer to absolute versus relative features of singletons (Gaspelin & Luck, 2018a), but these terms are not to be confused with first-versus second-order image statistics (Julesz, 1975; Lu & Sperling, 2001)."
  ]
